00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:33.990
It was very instructive
working on a second book.

00:04:33.990 --> 00:04:35.640
I know you hear about
sophomore slumps,

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:37.500
and you hear about
going back to the well,

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.722
and how difficult it can be.

00:04:39.722 --> 00:04:41.430
With the first book,
I think most people,

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:44.220
you feel an urgency to
kind of tell your story,

00:04:44.220 --> 00:04:45.902
to get your voice
out into the world.

00:04:45.902 --> 00:04:47.610
There's a certain
propulsion behind that,

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:50.760
to get your thoughts
you've had kicking around

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:53.340
in your head for quite some
time out and onto the page,

00:04:53.340 --> 00:04:55.050
and then into people's hands.

00:04:55.050 --> 00:04:57.920
And as with many
writers, my first book

00:04:57.920 --> 00:04:59.920
was semi-autobiographical,
and I mean more of it

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:02.400
is conjured than
people might think.

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:04.650
But that had a certain
movement to it,

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:06.190
because I felt urgency about it.

00:05:06.190 --> 00:05:09.140
I felt like I knew who
the characters were,

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:10.160
I knew the character.

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:11.960
It'd be written in first person.

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:14.420
It would be-- the
12-year-old Indian boy--

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:16.691
the first book, "Blue Boy"
is about-- it takes place

00:05:16.691 --> 00:05:18.440
in a very fixed period
of time in the life

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:20.510
of a 12-year-old
Indian-American boy growing up

00:05:20.510 --> 00:05:23.450
in the Midwest, who thinks he's
the reincarnation of Krishnaji,

00:05:23.450 --> 00:05:24.230
the Hindu god.

00:05:24.230 --> 00:05:27.201
So there's almost a
construct established

00:05:27.201 --> 00:05:28.700
at the beginning
of that book, where

00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:30.440
he goes through
certain exercises

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:33.080
to almost make his life
match the life of Krishnaji.

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:35.270
So there was almost
a roadmap I created

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:37.100
for myself to finish that book.

00:05:37.100 --> 00:05:40.032
And it was just a question
of pushing myself to do it.

00:05:40.032 --> 00:05:41.240
This book was very different.

00:05:41.240 --> 00:05:43.340
Because I began
writing it not sure

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:45.170
if it was going to be
a short story or what

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:47.330
it was really going
to end up being.

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:48.290
And what happened is--

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:51.080
the central
relationship in the book

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:53.130
is-- there are two main
characters in the book.

00:05:53.130 --> 00:05:56.926
One is a middle-aged
Indian man in his--

00:05:56.926 --> 00:05:59.930
he's in his mid-40s, who lives
in Cleveland with his mother.

00:05:59.930 --> 00:06:02.289
And you find at the
beginning of the book that--

00:06:02.289 --> 00:06:03.830
I might read from
that later, so I'll

00:06:03.830 --> 00:06:04.940
tell you what you
find out later--

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:06.560
but that's one of
the main characters.

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:08.630
And the other
character is a woman

00:06:08.630 --> 00:06:10.640
in her mid-40's,
who has just seen

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:13.520
her first, her only child,
her son, off to college,

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:15.050
and is sort of
unhappily married.

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:18.620
And to keep herself enthused,
she writes paranormal romances

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:19.240
as a secret.

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:22.100
So it's about how the two
of them become friends.

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:24.590
But that made that first
character I mentioned,

00:06:24.590 --> 00:06:27.050
he came from the idea
that years ago, I

00:06:27.050 --> 00:06:30.500
had a family friend whose
uncle came to town to visit.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:32.250
And if you know
Indian people, uncle

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:34.000
is a catch-all term
that can mean anything

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.759
from an actual uncle to some
tenuous familial connection

00:06:36.759 --> 00:06:37.800
that you don't even like.

00:06:37.800 --> 00:06:44.000
So i met a family friend of
his, who was in his mid-40s.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:44.840
He was unmarried.

00:06:44.840 --> 00:06:47.250
He lived with his
mother in New Jersey.

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:49.850
And I remember everybody having
this implicit understanding

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:52.280
about him, that because
all those things were true,

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:53.330
he had to be gay.

00:06:53.330 --> 00:06:55.100
Because that was
the only reason that

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:59.400
could explain having that
kind of life, so to speak.

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:01.400
And I remember being
doubly disheartened

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:03.260
by that, because
one, I was obviously

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:05.750
a closeted teenager
in the Midwest

00:07:05.750 --> 00:07:10.790
and found that kind of gossip
not particularly encouraging.

00:07:10.790 --> 00:07:13.880
But also, in addition to that,
and an extension of that,

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:16.070
people were framing
his life for him.

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:17.954
There was no-- he had
no agency in the way

00:07:17.954 --> 00:07:19.370
that people were
talking about him

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:21.200
and what his story might be.

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:23.570
So I started writing
that character.

00:07:23.570 --> 00:07:26.385
I felt like because my first
book was a younger character,

00:07:26.385 --> 00:07:28.510
there were certain queer
themes that were explored.

00:07:28.510 --> 00:07:30.301
And I felt a responsibility
to kind of talk

00:07:30.301 --> 00:07:32.720
to people at a different
point in their lives.

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:34.465
And be completely
frank, when I was

00:07:34.465 --> 00:07:35.840
writing that
character initially,

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:36.900
I was incredibly lonely.

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:39.600
My life as a single,
not happily single,

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:42.170
and I was dealing with all
of these issues of like kind

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:45.710
of what it means to be
lonely, and if that's

00:07:45.710 --> 00:07:49.280
your default state, if that
can be made productive at all.

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:52.280
And the more I began to write
that character-- actually,

00:07:52.280 --> 00:07:54.740
when I initially
started writing him,

00:07:54.740 --> 00:07:56.810
I didn't really think
about necessarily

00:07:56.810 --> 00:07:58.860
what his sexuality
was going to be.

00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:00.680
And then when I thought
about the themes

00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:02.000
I was really trying
to capture and what

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.170
I was trying to do
with that character,

00:08:03.170 --> 00:08:05.450
I realized actually it's
much more compelling

00:08:05.450 --> 00:08:08.060
if he is in fact
queer in some way,

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:11.580
and he doesn't even know what
he thinks about the world.

00:08:11.580 --> 00:08:15.800
So because of that-- and again,
laziness comes into play here.

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:17.560
Because there were
different threads,

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:18.590
there are those two
main characters,

00:08:18.590 --> 00:08:20.423
and there are a lot of
auxiliary characters.

00:08:20.423 --> 00:08:22.854
And the book is told in a
close third person among them.

00:08:22.854 --> 00:08:24.770
I would get really lazy
writing one character,

00:08:24.770 --> 00:08:25.650
not sure what was happening.

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:26.750
And then I would just
jump to the other one,

00:08:26.750 --> 00:08:27.620
and start writing that.

00:08:27.620 --> 00:08:28.700
And then I would
jump to the other one

00:08:28.700 --> 00:08:29.660
and start writing that.

00:08:29.660 --> 00:08:31.160
And then when you
go back, it really

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:32.909
makes your job much
harder, because if you

00:08:32.909 --> 00:08:35.450
want to create a cohesive
narrative, as a writer,

00:08:35.450 --> 00:08:37.190
it's not great to
do that to yourself.

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:39.815
Because you are like, oh, where
was I, and what does this mean.

00:08:39.815 --> 00:08:41.576
And what was I
thinking a year ago,

00:08:41.576 --> 00:08:43.159
when I was writing
that other section.

00:08:43.159 --> 00:08:46.850
So all this to say, I made
it much harder for myself.

00:08:46.850 --> 00:08:48.570
It was much harder.

00:08:48.570 --> 00:08:50.690
But I certainly
learned things going

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:53.340
into the next project I work
on, of like how not to do that,

00:08:53.340 --> 00:08:56.600
how to keep a better idea,
a work ethic in mind that

00:08:56.600 --> 00:08:58.997
will keep me on track.

00:08:58.997 --> 00:09:00.830
MELISSA POULOS: Well,
